title: For Sale:  Darne Halifaz Double Barrel Shotgun, France
postcontent: Hello.  I don't know alot about this.  Here is what I do know.  Darne was (is?) a very high quality and expensive French gun make who started making double guns in about 1880.  The shorguns were sometimes highly engraved and sometimes plain but all exhibited the best workmanship and materials.  During the time between the wars, Darne made a lower priced series called the Halifax.  I believe all Darne guns exhibited the slide open action that this halifax exhibits.  I am not sure but I believe this shotgun to be from about 1920-1935.  I don't see a serial number.  The barrels are not Damscuss and are 27.5 inches long.  I do not know the chokes n the barrels but I assume left improved or Modified and right full.  It is 12 guage.  The action is the typical DArne slide open action.  It is minimally engraved.  The walnut is chequered on the fore arm but not on the butt stock.  Wood shows wear and some finish checkering but is in tact.  Double triggers.  Action is very tight.  Triggers are a tad heavey but very crisp with no creep and not much over travel.  This gun comes up like a dream.  I had a collecter who told me the gun was worth 2500 to 4000 bucks.  Unfortunately, he was not willing to give me 4 grand for it.  So I am selling it.  I invite you to comelook at it.  I have taken it to a few local gun shows and most people knew very little about it (or any French or English shotguns).  I will take it to Wanenmachers in OCT if it doesn't sell here.  No Trades please.  Marco REDACTED
